   <titles>
      <title>Squeeze Theorem: Illustration</title>
   </titles>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>If a sequence <math>
                     <latex>(x_n)</latex>
                  </math> is squeezed between two sequences <math>
                     <latex>(a_n)</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>(b_n)</latex>
                  </math> which converge to the same number <math>
                     <latex>c</latex>
                  </math>, then <math>
                     <latex>(x_n)</latex>
                  </math> also converges to <math>
                     <latex>c</latex>
                  </math>. Intuitively this is quite plausible as the graphic below shows.</para.body>
            </para>
            <media type="image" active="0" inline="0">
               <img src="ims/SqueezeTheorem.png"/>
            </media>
            <para>
               <para.body>The sequence elements of <math>
                     <latex>(x_n)</latex>
                  </math> are represented by red dots; those of <math>
                     <latex>(a_n)</latex>
                  </math> by blue dots, and those of <math>
                     <latex>(b_n)</latex>
                  </math> by pale green dots.</para.body>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>Now <math>
                     <latex>(a_n)</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>(b_n)</latex>
                  </math> converge to  the same limit <math>
                     <latex>c</latex>
                  </math>. In such a situation the elements of <math>
                     <latex>(x_n)</latex>
                  </math> have no place to go but to converge to <math>
                     <latex>c</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
